  "body": "<!-- Have you done the following? -->\r\n<!--   * read the Code of Conduct? By filing an Issue, you are expected to -->  \r\n<!--     comply with it, including treating everyone with respect: -->\r\n<!--     https://github.com/hyperledger/besu/blob/main/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md -->\r\n<!--   * Reproduced the issue in the latest version of the software -->\r\n<!--   * Read the debugging docs: https://besu.hyperledger.org/en/stable/HowTo/Monitor/Logging/ -->\r\n<!--   * Duplicate Issue check:  https://github.com/search?q=+is%3Aissue+repo%3Ahyperledger/Besu -->\r\n<!-- Note:  Not all sections will apply to all issue types. -->\r\n\r\n### Description\r\nWhen besu is using bonsai storage and doing a fast-sync, re-pivoting to a new block causes besu to re-start the worldstate download.  \r\n\r\nThis means a fast-sync bonsai node is in a race to download its entire worldstate before its peers are no longer able to serve it.  \r\n\r\n### Acceptance Criteria\r\n* bonsai fast-sync nodes should not restart worldstate download on re-pivot\r\n\r\n### Steps to Reproduce (Bug)\r\n1. fast-sync mainnet with besu on bonsai\r\n2. observe the worldstate downlod re-start upon fast-sync re-pivoting\r\n\r\n**Expected behavior:** [What you expect to happen]\r\n* bonsai fast-sync nodes should continue to download worldstate on a re-pivot\r\n* at the end of fast-sync the worldstate trie should implement a 'heal' process similar to snap-sync\r\n\r\n**Actual behavior:** [What actually happens]\r\n* besu re-starts the woldstate download on re-pivot\r\n\r\n**Frequency:** [What percentage of the time does it occur?]\r\npredictably with slower hardware, and slower upstream internet connections\r\n\r\n### Versions (Add all that apply)\r\n* Software version: [`besu --version`] 22.1.x\r\n",
